As longas we are content with Quintilian's general exposition, all is simple. The allegory is satisfied when the commonwealth, in danger os relapsing into civil war, has become a sea-wearied ship, driiting back into the storm. The masts, the sails, the pine oi Pontus, the Cyclades, belong to the ship, and we must not look for their exact couuterparts in the State. Here, as with other allegories, we are beset with difficulties the moment we attempt to fit the details more exactly. It has been argued. from vv. 17, 18, that Horace speaks of the ship as ii he had himself leit it (but see notes on those verses), and that the subject oi the Ode must, therefore, be not the State but the Republican party. Why, others ask, is ita Pontio piae, not some other—idean. perhaps, as more suitable to the mythical origin oi Rome? Acron suggested the answer, which has since been developed into a whole theory ol the purpose os the Ode. Pompey was the conqueror of Mithridates of Pontus. The ship, therefore, represents the inmunes ot' lris son, Sextus Pompeius, whom Horace would dissuade from embarking again in war with Octavianus atter the treaty oi Misenum, rac. 39.

The difficulties os interpretation seemed so great to Muretus, Dacier, and Bentley, that they refused to allow the Ode to be allegorical at all.

On our view there will be nothing to fix it to a definite date. The ship is in sight oi harbour. This distinguishes the Ode from Epodes vii. and xvi. (see the Introductions to them). It is not yet moored beyond the resch oi the wind.
